    "oe": [
     {
      "bron": "HAVO Engels CE 2023 Tijdvak 1 Leesvaardigheid (geen afbeelding)",
      "ctx": "Fragment from an opinion article:\n\n\"Social media companies claim they protect young users, yet their own internal research shows that Instagram makes body image issues worse for one in three teenage girls. The platforms profit from engagement, and outrage drives engagement more than anything else.\"",
      "v": "(a) What is the main argument of this passage?\n(b) The writer uses the word \"yet\" in the first sentence. What function does this word have?",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) The main argument is that social media companies prioritise profit over the wellbeing of young users, despite claiming otherwise.\n(b) \"Yet\" introduces a contrast: it shows that the companies' actions contradict their claims. It signals that what follows undermines the first statement."
     },
     {
      "bron": "HAVO Engels CE 2022 Tijdvak 2 Leesvaardigheid (geen afbeelding)",
      "ctx": "Fragment from a science article:\n\n\"The octopus has three hearts, blue blood, and a brain that wraps around its throat. Two-thirds of its neurons are in its arms, which means each arm can taste, touch and move independently. Scientists believe this decentralised nervous system is key to the octopus's remarkable intelligence.\"",
      "v": "(a) According to the text, why is the octopus considered intelligent?\n(b) What does \"this\" in \"this decentralised nervous system\" refer to?",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) The octopus is considered intelligent because of its decentralised nervous system: most neurons are in its arms, allowing each arm to function independently.\n(b) \"This\" refers to the fact that two-thirds of the neurons are in the arms rather than in a central brain, giving each arm independent sensing and movement capabilities."
     },
     {
      "bron": "HAVO Engels CE 2024 Tijdvak 1 Leesvaardigheid (geen afbeelding)",
      "ctx": "Fragment from a travel essay:\n\n\"Tourism can be a double-edged sword. While it brings revenue and jobs to remote communities, it can also erode the very culture and landscapes that attract visitors in the first place. Venice, Barcelona and Dubrovnik have all struggled with overtourism.\"",
      "v": "(a) Explain the metaphor \"double-edged sword\" in this context.\n(b) What tone does the writer adopt: enthusiastic, balanced, or dismissive? Justify your answer.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) A double-edged sword means something that has both positive and negative effects. Here: tourism brings economic benefits but simultaneously damages culture and environment.\n(b) Balanced. The writer acknowledges both advantages (revenue, jobs) and disadvantages (erosion of culture, overtourism) without clearly favouring one side."
     },
     {
      "bron": "Artikel",
      "ctx": "Opening of a news article:\n\n\"Scientists have discovered a new species of deep-sea fish near the Mariana Trench. The fish, named Pseudoliparis belyaevi, was found at a depth of 8,336 metres, making it the deepest fish ever recorded on camera. The research team from the University of Western Australia described the discovery as 'breathtaking'.\"",
      "v": "(a) What is the purpose of this text: to inform, to persuade, or to entertain? Explain your answer.\n(b) Who is the most likely intended audience for this article? Give a reason.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) To inform. The text presents factual information (species name, depth, institution) in an objective tone with no attempt to change the reader's opinion or to primarily entertain.\n(b) A general educated audience / the general public. The article avoids highly technical language and is written in a clear, accessible style, suggesting it is aimed at a broad readership rather than specialists."
     },
     {
      "bron": "Artikel",
      "ctx": "Two extracts about plastic pollution:\n\nText A: \"Every year, approximately 8 million tonnes of plastic enter the oceans. Studies show plastic has been found in the bodies of 90% of seabirds. Microplastics have been detected in human blood.\"\n\nText B: \"Plastic is destroying our planet. The oceans are being murdered by greed. We are poisoning ourselves and our children every single day.\"",
      "v": "(a) Which text is more reliable as a source of information? Give two reasons.\n(b) Identify one language technique used in Text B and explain its effect.",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) Text A is more reliable because: (1) it uses specific statistics and quantifiable data (\"8 million tonnes\", \"90%\"), and (2) it refers to scientific studies, suggesting the claims have been verified by research. Text B uses emotional language without evidence.\n(b) Any one of: emotive language (\"murdering\", \"poisoning\") — creates a strong emotional reaction in the reader; hyperbole (\"destroying our planet\") — exaggerates to emphasise the problem; second person (\"ourselves and our children\") — makes the reader feel personally involved/threatened."
     },
     {
      "bron": "Artikel",
      "ctx": "Paragraph from an article about fast fashion:\n\n\"Fast fashion brands release up to 52 micro-seasons per year, encouraging consumers to buy more and discard more. As a result, the fashion industry produces 10% of global carbon emissions — more than international aviation and shipping combined. Furthermore, water consumption for textile production is enormous: it takes 2,700 litres of water to produce a single cotton T-shirt, enough drinking water for one person for 2.5 years.\"",
      "v": "(a) How does the writer structure the argument in this paragraph? Refer to specific words or phrases.\n(b) The writer uses the statistic about a T-shirt and drinking water. What is the effect of presenting the information this way?",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) The writer builds the argument using cause-and-effect structure and then adds evidence using discourse markers: \"As a result\" signals consequence (consumption → emissions); \"Furthermore\" adds another supporting point (water use). Each sentence introduces a new layer of evidence.\n(b) By comparing the water needed for a T-shirt to a person's drinking water for 2.5 years, the writer makes an abstract statistic concrete and relatable. This comparison helps the reader understand the true scale of the problem, making the argument more persuasive and memorable."
     },
     {
      "bron": "Artikel",
      "ctx": "Concluding paragraph of an opinion piece:\n\n\"It is clear that schools must take responsibility for teaching media literacy. Young people are bombarded with misinformation daily. If they cannot distinguish reliable sources from biased ones, democracy itself is at risk. Teachers, curriculum designers and governments must act — before it is too late.\"",
      "v": "(a) Is the final sentence (\"Teachers, curriculum designers and governments must act — before it is too late.\") a fact or an opinion? Explain.\n(b) What rhetorical technique does the writer use in the phrase \"before it is too late\", and what effect does it have?",
      "o": [
       ""
      ],
      "c": 0,
      "u": "(a) It is an opinion. It expresses the writer's personal view about what should happen (\"must act\"). It cannot be objectively verified as true or false — it is a recommendation/call to action, not a statement of fact.\n(b) The technique is urgency / apocalyptic language (or: emotive language / implied threat). The effect is to pressure the reader into agreeing: by suggesting that inaction will lead to disaster, the writer creates a sense of crisis that makes the demand feel non-negotiable and immediate."
     }
    ],
